%T A093505 27,27,29,29,30,32,33,33,34,36,36,38,39,39,40,42,43,43,45,45,46,48,48,
%U A093505 50,51,51,53,53,54,56,57,57,58,60,60,62,63,63,65
%N A093505 a(n) = floor(A001969(n)/2 + 1/2).
%C A093505 The sequence is a quasi-inverse of A161560: For n >= 2, a(A161560(n+1)+1) = n or n-1. - _Jaroslav Krizek_, Jun 13 2009, corrected Jul 13 2012
%C A093505 Conjecture: Essentially partial sums of A036577 (true for at least 10000 terms). - _Sean A. Irvine_, Jul 17 2022
%C A093505 From _Bartlomiej Pawlik_, Apr 19 2026: (Start)
%C A093505 Proof of the conjecture:
%C A093505 Let z(n) be the position of the n-th 0 in the binary Thue-Morse sequence A010060, with z(0) = 0. Since A001969 lists the indices of 0's in A010060, we have z(n) = A001969(n+1). Also, A036577 gives the number of 1's between successive 0's in A010060, so A036577(n+1) = z(n+1) - z(n) - 1.
%C A093505 Therefore, for n >= 1, Sum_{k=1..n-1} A036577(k) = Sum_{k=0..n-2} (z(k+1) - z(k) - 1) = z(n-1) - (n-1) = A001969(n) - n + 1 = a(n).
%C A093505 Hence a(n) is exactly the sequence of partial sums of A036577, with initial term a(1) = 0.
%C A093505 a(k) is the number of 1's before the (k+1)-th 0 in binary Thue-Morse sequence A010060. (End)
%F A093505 a(n) = A001969(n) - n + 1 for n >= 2. - _Jaroslav Krizek_, Jun 13 2009
%e A093505 a(5) = 5 because the fifth evil number = 9 and floor(9/2 + 1/2) = 5.
%o A093505 (PARI) a(n)=(2*n+hammingweight(n-1)%2-1)\2 \\ _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Mar 22 2013
%Y A093505 Cf. A001969, A000069, A036577.
